# Chains

The filter table is used for packet filtering.
iptables -t filter -L

- Input – incoming connections. For example, if a user attempts to SSH into your PC/server
- Forward – This chain is used for incoming connections that aren’t actually being delivered locally. router – data is always being sent to it but rarely actually destined for the router itself
- Output – This chain is used for outgoing connections. For example, if you try to ping howtogeek.com,

When using iptables to lock down your system, remember that a lot of protocols will require two-way communication

# Policy Chain Default Behavior

iptables --policy INPUT DROP
iptables --policy OUTPUT ACCEPT
iptables --policy FORWARD DROP
or -P
iptables -L | grep policy

# Respons

- Accept – Allow the connection.
- Drop – Drop the connection, act like it never happened.
- Reject – drops but sends error

# Commands

iptables starts at the top of its list and goes through each rule until it finds one that it matches
-A to append rules to the existing chain.
-I [chain] [number] to specify the number it should be in the list.

iptables -A INPUT -s 10.10.10.10 -j DROP #drop all from ip
iptables -A INPUT -s 10.10.10.0/24 -j DROP #range
iptables -A INPUT -s 10.10.10.0/255.255.255.0 -j DROP
iptables -A INPUT -i eth1 -s 10.1.1.0/24 -p tcp -j ACCEPT
iptables -A OUTPUT -o eth1 -d 10.1.1.0/24 -p tcp -j ACCEPT

iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport ssh -s 10.10.10.10 -j DROP
iptables -A INPUT -p udp --dport 51280 -s 10.10.10.10 -j DROP #drop 51280/udp from ip

lo is loopback interface
